- Operations on str data
a) Indexing
- The purpose of indexing operation is that "to get one value at a time from str object".
- In otherwords, The Processing of Obtaining One Value from str object by passing valid index is called indexing

‚û°Ô∏è syntax : strobj[index] +ve or -ve
- Here strobj is an object of <class,'str'>
- if we enter valid index then we get corresponding value from str object.
- if we enter invalid index then we get indexError as a Result.

‚û°Ô∏è‚û°Ô∏è‚û°Ô∏è‚û°Ô∏è‚û°Ô∏è  Lecture  16 ‚û°Ô∏è‚û°Ô∏è‚û°Ô∏è‚û°Ô∏è‚û°Ô∏è

b) slicing Operation
- Slicing is the operation of extracting a portion (subsequence) of data from sequences like lists, strings, tuples, arrays, etc.
- It uses the indexing operator [:] with optional parameters:
sequence[start:stop:step]

‚û°Ô∏è  Purpose
- To access subsets of data without modifying the original sequence.
- To manipulate sequences efficiently (e.g., reversing, skipping elements, trimming)
- To simplify code by avoiding loops for extracting parts of sequences.

Syntax
 üëâ
syntax-1: strobj[Beginindex:Endindex]

- This Syntax gives of Range Chars from BEGINING INDEX TO ENDINDEX-1 provied BeginIndex < ENDINDEX Otherwise we get Space or '' as Result


üëâ
syntax-2: strobj [Beginindex:]
- In This we specify begin index and we don't specify 
- If we don't specify END Index Then PVM takes END index as len(strobj)

- If we don't specify END Index then pvm takes the tange of chars from begin index to last character.
    OR
- This syntax gives RAnge of char from Begin index to last character.


üëâ 
syntax-3: StrObj[:Endindex]
- In This we specify END index and we don't specify BEGIN Index 
- If we don't specify BEGIN Index Then PVM takes BEGIN index as Either 0 (+ve) or -len(strObj).

- If we don't specify BEGIN Index then pvm takes the Range of chars from first character END index-1.
    OR
- This syntax gives RAnge of char from Begin index to last character.


